://api.github.com/users/anicolson/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2020-07-07T12:25:31Z","updated_at":"2020-07-07T12:25:31Z","author_association":"OWNER","body":"Hi,\r\n\r\nFor 1., yes, a training set with longer files should be used. What would be interesting is to see a histogram of the durations of all the clean speech files in the training set.\r\n\r\nFor 2, certainly, the network has less information to infer from. \r\n\r\nFor 3, for the split files, is the speech closer to the start of the file than the files that are not split?\r\n\r\nFor 4, the noise files are scaled in the time domain, not frequency domain. This is certainly an issue that can be looked into to improve the framework.\r\n\r\nFor 5, the network has been trained with only a single speaker as the target, so it may struggle with multiple speakers.\r\n\r\nHope this helps,\r\nAaron.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/anicolson/DeepXi/issues/comments/654819909/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null,"event":"commented","actor":{"login":"anicolson","id":26111230,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjI2MTExMjMw","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/26111230?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson","html_url":"https://github.com/anicolson","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/anicolson/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false}},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/anicolson/DeepXi/issues/comments/655701050","html_url":"https://github.com/anicolson/DeepXi/issues/44#issuecomment-655701050","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/anicolson/DeepXi/issues/44","id":655701050,"node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY1NTcwMTA1MA==","user":{"login":"ahikaml","id":32457828,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjMyNDU3ODI4","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/32457828?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml","html_url":"https://github.com/ahikaml","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2020-07-08T19:06:26Z","updated_at":"2020-07-08T19:06:26Z","author_association":"NONE","body":"Hi,\r\n\r\nThanks for your response. It's very helpful.\r\n\r\nRegarding (1) see for example the VCTK histogram below. Most of the files are shorter than the net receptive field.\r\nIn the other hand, as I said, somehow the conversion time in the inference is lower when the net is trained on shorter files (up to 2 secs). \r\n\r\nRegarding (3) - No. In long files I just cut any extra silence in the beginning to make the learning as effective as possible. \r\n\r\nRegarding (4) - I assumed that scaling in the time domain is identical to scaling in the frequency domain (Parseval's theorem). If you meant to a different scaling factor per frequency bin then it's not different than equalization.  \r\nLet me know if you think I'm wrong.   \r\nAnyway I thought that scaling by the maximum or by some upper percentile might give a decent solution for this issue but I wasn't really sure. I guess I'll have to try...\r\n\r\nOne more question - is there a good way to know, after the training, what is the effective receptive field size? I mean by looking on the coefficient values of any specific layer? Could it be related to the coefficients values in the residual blocks with the highest dilation ratio?\r\n\r\nThanks\r\nAhikam\r\n\r\n![DurationHistVCTK](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32457828/86958926-9db58c80-c165-11ea-921a-77e9e12e67f9.JPG)\r\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/anicolson/DeepXi/issues/comments/655701050/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null,"event":"commented","actor":{"login":"ahikaml","id":32457828,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjMyNDU3ODI4","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/32457828?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml","html_url":"https://github.com/ahikaml","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/u