r}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2020-07-09T05:54:18Z","updated_at":"2020-07-09T05:54:18Z","author_association":"NONE","body":"Thanks for the link. It seems that this site helps you to calculate the theoretical receptive field, i.e. the maximum that the network can \"see\" back to the past . \r\nHowever to me it feels that sometimes, depends on the training data, the network can \"choose\" not to look on such a long history even though its architecture supports that. \r\nFor example when the network has receptive field of 6 sec but it learn that information of more than 2 seconds back to the past isn't relevant to the current SNR.\r\n \r\nIn such case I believe that its coefficients will be updated accordingly to represent this short receptive field. \r\nSo.. the question is: can I recognized such situations by looking on the network coefficient after the training, or it's totally a black box and all we can do is just checking if the 'a priory' SNR we got from the net is accurate enough?\r\n\r\nThanks\r\nAhikam\r\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/anicolson/DeepXi/issues/comments/655917519/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null,"event":"commented","actor":{"login":"ahikaml","id":32457828,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjMyNDU3ODI4","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/32457828?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml","html_url":"https://github.com/ahikaml","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ahikaml/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/use